is attached:

Ribosomes
Ribosomes are small, dense, spherical organelles present in all living cells. They are known
as the protein factories of the cell because their main function is to synthesize proteins by translating genetic information from mRNA.

Structure
Ribosomes are made of rRNA (ribosomal RNA) and proteins.
They have two subunits:
Large subunit
Small subunit
In eukaryotic cells: 80S ribosomes (60S + 40S)
In prokaryotic cells: 70S ribosomes (50S + 30S)
S = Svedberg unit (sedimentation rate during centrifugation)

Location
Free in the cytoplasm
Attached to rough endoplasmic reticulum (RER)
Inside mitochondria and chloroplasts (have their own ribosomes)

Functions
Protein synthesis (translation)
Free ribosomes make proteins used inside the cell
Bound ribosomes (on RER) make proteins for:

Cell membrane
Secretion outside the cell
Lysosomes
Importance
Essential for growth and repair
Presence of ribosomes is a key feature of all living cells

**Lysosomes
Lysosomes are membrane-bound cell organelles found in eukaryotic cells, especially animal cells.
They are known as the “suicidal bags of the cell” because they contain powerful digestive enzymes that 
can break down harmful substances and even the cell itself if needed.

Structure
Single-membrane bound organelles
Contain hydrolytic enzymes (digestive enzymes like proteases, lipases, nucleases, etc.)
Work best in acidic pH

Functions
Digestion of unwanted materials
Break down worn-out cell organelles (autophagy)
Destroy foreign particles like bacteria (defense)
Cell digestion if damaged (autolysis — leads to cell self-destruction)
Helps in intracellular digestion
Helps in recycling cellular components

Location
Present in animal cells
Rare or absent in plant cells (plants usually use vacuoles for digestion)

Why Called Suicidal Bags?
Because when lysosomes burst, enzymes leak into the cytoplasm and digest the cell.

Key Points to Remember
Formed by Golgi apparatus
Contain hydrolytic enzymes
pH inside lysosome is acidic
Important in cell defense and waste removal

Mitochondria
Mitochondria are double-membrane cell organelles found in eukaryotic cells and are known as the “powerhouse of the cell”
because they produce energy in the form of ATP (Adenosine Triphosphate).

Structure
Double membrane:
Outer membrane: smooth
Inner membrane: folded into structures called cristae
Cristae increase surface area for energy production
Matrix: inner fluid-filled space containing enzymes, DNA, ribosomes
Possess circular DNA and 70S ribosomes (like bacteria)

Functions
Energy production through cellular respiration
Convert glucose and oxygen into ATP
Heat production in some cells
Regulate cell metabolism
Play role in apoptosis (programmed cell death)

Special Features
Semi-autonomous organelle (can replicate on its own)
Inherited maternal DNA (passed from mother to offspring)
Cells needing more energy (e.g., muscle cells, sperm tail) contain more mitochondria

| Feature        | Description                    |
| -------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Nickname       | Powerhouse of the cell         |
| Membrane       | Double membrane                |
| Inner membrane | Cristae                        |
| Contains       | DNA, ribosomes, enzymes        |
| Function       | ATP production via respiration |
| Found in       | Eukaryotic cells               |

Plastids
Plastids are large, membrane-bound organelles found mainly in plant cells and algae. 
They are important for photosynthesis, storage, and pigment synthesis. Plastids are absent in animal cells.

types:
| Type             | Function                           | Example / Pigment                                              |
| ---------------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Chloroplasts** | Photosynthesis                     | Contain **chlorophyll** (green pigment)                        |
| **Chromoplasts** | Provide colour to fruits & flowers | Contain pigments like **carotene, xanthophyll**                |
| **Leucoplasts**  | Storage of food                    | Amyloplast (starch), Elaioplast (fat), Proteinoplast (protein) |

✅ Structure
Double-membrane organelle
Inside fluid called stroma
Have thylakoids stacked into grana (in chloroplasts)
Contain :
DNA
Ribosomes (70S)
Enzymes
Because of their own DNA & ribosomes, plastids can replicate independently → hence called semi-autonomous organelles

✅ Functions
Photosynthesis (in chloroplasts)
Storage of food (starch, fat, protein)
Give colour to flowers and fruits
Synthesis of important organic molecules
